# Cortisol levels linked to type 2 diabetes
Researchers at Ohio State University have found a clear link between the
stress hormone cortisol and higher blood glucose levels in people with type 2
The study published online in the journal Psychoneuroendocrinology.
"In healthy people, cortisol fluctuates naturally throughout the day, spiking
in the morning and falling at night," said Dr. Joshua J. Joseph, an
"But in participants with type 2 diabetes, cortisol profiles that were flatter
Previous research has shown that stress and depression are two of the major
causes of a flatter cortisol profile. These sustained levels of cortisol make
it much more difficult to control blood glucose and manage the condition,
which is why it is so important for those with type 2 diabetes to find ways to
"We have begun a new trial to examine if mindfulness practices can lower blood
glucose in those with type 2 diabetes," said Joseph.
"But this isn't the only effective form of stress relief. It's important to
find something you enjoy and make it a part of your everyday routine."
The relationship of cortisol with glucose levels was only observed in those
with diabetes. However, Dr. Joseph and his team believe the stress hormone
likely plays an important role in diabetes prevention and they continue to
research the connection between cortisol and the development of diabetes and
More than one million Australians live with type 2 diabetes, which means their
bodies aren’t using insulin effectively. Some people can manage their blood
glucose levels with healthy eating and exercise, while others may need
Most people with type 2 diabetes know the importance of exercising regularly,
eating a healthy diet, and getting plenty of rest. But stress relief is a
crucial and often forgotten component of diabetes management.
Whether it's a yoga class, taking a walk, or reading a book, finding ways to
lower your stress levels is important to everyone's overall health, especially
